The Battle of Glasgow, fought on October 15, 1864, was part of Price's Missouri Expedition during the American Civil War. Confederate forces, led by Generals John B. Clark and Joe Shelby, attacked Glasgow with artillery and infantry, forcing the Union forces under Colonel Chester Harding to surrender. The Confederates captured Union weapons and supplies and set fire to the town, including the City Hall and several homes. After the battle, the town was left without protection, leading to further violence by guerrilla groups. The Union forces suffered 30 casualties, while the Confederates lost around 50 men. [CLIPEND]
